# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-daniel-meier
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The **1st Louisiana Regiment Cavalry** was a cavalry unit in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The regiment was one of several organized in New Orleans in August 1862 by order of Maj.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] Butler and recruited from among "white Unionists, and pro-Northern refugees" in the city; it consisted primarily of foreigners and men of Northern birth.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The unit was assigned in 1863 to the Union XIX Corps of Maj.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] They participated in operations in Western Louisiana: Fort Bisland, Irish Bend, and Vermilion Bayou in April, 1863 and in the Siege of Port Hudson from May to July.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The regiment participated in the Red River Campaign from March to May, 1864.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The unit left Louisiana and moved to Fort Barrancas, Florida in February 1865.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] It joined the campaign against Mobile, Alabama.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The regiment then marched to Blakeley, across the Mobile River, taking control of its Fort Blakeley, a major fort during the war.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] This completed Confederate defeat in the area.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The unit mustered out on December 18, 1865.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] The 2nd Louisiana Regiment Cavalry was originally organized as the 3rd Louisiana Infantry in New Orleans on November 25, 1863.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/1st-louisiana-regiment-cavalry-union] After serving at the defenses of Brashear City, Baton Rouge and Port Hudson, the unit was consolidated with 1st Louisiana Cavalry on September 7, 1864.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Louis in 1841, son of a native German hardware merchant Adolphus Meier.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Louis Public High School, he studied at Washington University in St.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Louis for two years, and at the Royal Polytechnic College in Hanover for another four years.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Upon his return in the States in 1862 he started as apprentice at Mason's Locomotive Works in Taunton, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] The next year he enlisted in the Grey Reserves, the Thirty-Second Pennsylvania, which was attached to the army of the Potomac until after the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] He subsequently served in the Second Massachusetts Battery, also in the United States Army Corps of Engineers, and finally became lieutenant in the First Louisiana Cavalry, seeing much active service, and on May 30, 1865, receiving the surrender of Lieutenant-General John Bell Hood and staff.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] At the war Meier was connected with Rogers Locomotive and Machine Works in Paterson, New Jersey for a year.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] In 1867 he joined the Kansas Pacific Railway first as assistant and later as superintendent of machinery.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] In 1871 he became chief engineer of the Illinois Patent Coke Company for a year.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] In 1872 he became secretary of the Meier Iron Company, where he designed and build its blast furnaces for another year.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] From 1873 to 1875 he superintendent the St.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Louis Interstate Fair machinery department.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] During this time he became actively interested in the St.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Louis cotton industry and was associated with the St.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Louis Cotton Factory and with the Peper Hydraulic Cotton Press, for both of whom he designed machinery for compressing cotton.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] In 1884 Meier founded the Heine Safety Boiler Company for the development in the United States of the water-tube boiler of that name, and became its president and chief engineer.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] In those days he also joined the American Diesel Engine Company, where he introduced the Diesel motor into the United States.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Until 1908 he was its engineer-in-chief and treasurer of the company.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Meier participated in a number of professional organizations, such as the St.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Louis Engineers Club, the American Boiler Manufacturers Association, the Machinery and Metal Trades Association, and the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, where he was president in the year 1911–12.
[src:edward-daniel-meier/edward-daniel-meier] Daniel Meier died in New York City, December 15, 1914.
